, and note-taking tools. Covering a variety of methods for introducing students to the medieval and Renaissance reading practice known as commonplacing, this volume provides instructors with concrete guidelines for using commonplace books as a teaching and learning tool. The enclosed essays provide a point of reference for best practices as well as concrete models for teaching and learning with commonplace books, helping instructors develop more student-centred, inclusive curricula.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommonplace books. 0aMiddle AgesxStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aRenaissancexStudy and teaching (Higher). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  acommonplace books.  acommonplacing.  apedagogy.  ateaching Medieval Studies.1 aCorrigan, Nora L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckhardt, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstill, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagstrom-Schmidt, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker, Sarah E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParker, Sarah E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPasupathi, Vimala C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchumacher-Schmidt, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilva, Andie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilva, Andie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part